{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9778,"record_hash":"sha256:48bac1a17c96207617beb0945d02705f9694139e16d294d2a097db636f58bea2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:41.608Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n+# Agent Session Handoff Design\n+\n+This note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\n+primitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n+\n+## Goal\n+\n+Let a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\n+another machine, agent, or provider session.\n+\n+The target experience:\n+\n+1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n+2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n+3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n+4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n+5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n+   context\n+6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n+   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n+\n+This is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n+\n+## Current Building Blocks\n+\n+The primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n+\n+- durable project-scoped sessions\n+- capture turns within sessions\n+- ordered transcript records within each turn\n+- environment observations for each turn\n+- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n+- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n+- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n+\n+That is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\n+state to `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+## Design Bias\n+\n+The agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n+\n+That said, raw transcript access alone is not enough. Once sessions include\n+subagents, compactions, large backfills, and repeated captures, asking the next\n+agent to infer everything from a giant transcript is brittle and expensive.\n+\n+The useful middle ground is:\n+\n+- deterministic orientation commands\n+- bounded transcript hydration\n+- stable machine-readable JSON\n+- enough metadata to let the agent choose what to read next\n+- optional human-readable output for manual debugging\n+\n+Do not bake a model-generated summary into storage. If a summary exists later,\n+make it a derived convenience artifact, not the source of truth.\n+\n+## Challenge To The Initial Approach\n+\n+The core approach is right: let the next agent ask GitButler for relevant\n+context. The parts I would push on:\n+\n+- \"Relevant bits\" cannot mean \"dump all related transcripts.\" The first real\n+  branch already has a main session plus subagent sessions. Larger branches will\n+  have far more.\n+- The first command needs to orient the agent, not just list opaque session\n+  keys. It should expose counts, recency, agents, models, capture kinds, and\n+  highlighted turn keys.\n+- The next agent should be able to distinguish main-thread work from sidecar\n+  review/subagent work when that information exists. If provider metadata does\n+  not expose this cleanly, the CLI should still show enough facts for the agent\n+  to infer cautiously.\n+- Handoff should avoid pretending related means owned. A branch can have related\n+  sessions that are background review, experiments, or unrelated active\n+  worktree noise.\n+- We should not require GitButler app APIs for this. CLI plus `but-agentlog`\n+  primitives is the right first surface.\n+\n+## Agent-Facing Workflow\n+\n+A good first workflow is deliberately small:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog sessions branch <branch>\n+but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--turns N]\n+but agentlog related-detail branch <branch> <session-key> [--context-before N] [--context-after N]\n+```\n+\n+The exact names can change, but the shape matters:\n+\n+1. discover related sessions for the current target\n+2. inspect a compact session/turn outline\n+3. hydrate only the windows that look useful\n+\n+The user prompt can be simple:\n+\n+```text\n+Check whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n+```\n+\n+A future skill can teach agents this sequence, but the CLI should be sensible\n+without the skill.\n+\n+## Discovery Output\n+\n+The discovery command should answer:\n+\n+- which sessions are related to this branch/review/change?\n+- which turns caused that relationship?\n+- how recent are they?\n+- how much data would reading them cost?\n+- which agent/provider/model created them?\n+- are they mostly one large backfill or incremental ongoing work?\n+\n+Machine-readable output should include at least:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"target_kind\": \"branch\",\n+  \"target_key\": \"ref:refs/heads/example\",\n+  \"sessions\": [\n+    {\n+      \"session_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n+      \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-20T18:12:21.645Z\",\n+      \"source_count\": 1,\n+      \"turn_count\": 8,\n+      \"record_count\": 5785,\n+      \"related_turn_keys\": [\"sha256-...\"],\n+      \"agents\": [\"codex\"],\n+      \"providers\": [\"openai\"],\n+      \"models\": [\"gpt-5.5\"]\n+    }\n+  ]\n+}\n+```\n+\n+This is not a summary. It is an index card for choosing what to read.\n+\n+## Timeline Output\n+\n+The timeline command should show turn-level structure before hydrating full\n+records:\n+\n+- `turn_key`\n+- `previous_turn_key`\n+- `capture_kind`\n+- `captured_at`\n+- record count\n+- environment snapshot status\n+- observed branch/review/change keys\n+- first and last record timestamps\n+- maybe a tiny preview of first/last user text\n+\n+This gives the next agent a cheap way to decide whether to read:\n+\n+- the latest turns\n+- the highlighted related turns\n+- the whole main session\n+- sidecar/subagent sessions\n+\n+## Detail Hydration\n+\n+Hydration should return ordered transcript records grouped by capture turn.\n+\n+For handoff, the safest default is a bounded window:\n+\n+```text\n+related turns, plus a small amount of context before and after\n+```\n+\n+The agent can ask for more if needed. This mirrors normal file exploration:\n+start with an outline, then open the specific file region.\n+\n+## Subagents And Compactions\n+\n+Real data already shows multiple related sessions for one branch. Some are\n+sidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n+\n+The handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n+\n+- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n+- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n+  session id, often created close together\n+- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n+  prior conversation context\n+\n+Avoid hard-coding those labels until the source data supports them. For now,\n+expose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+- no provider-native resume\n+- no generated persistent handoff summary\n+- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n+- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n+- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n+- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Should the CLI expose one ergonomic `handoff` command, or keep only generic\n+  primitives and let a skill orchestrate them?\n+- Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n+  it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n+- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n+  sessions from spawned subagents?\n+- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n+  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n+- How much transcript text should human-readable output show by default?\n+\n+## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n+\n+Do not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command yet.\n+\n+First add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform\n+handoff:\n+\n+1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n+   keys\n+2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n+3. add a related-detail command that hydrates records around highlighted turns\n+4. write a small skill/workflow note that tells agents how to use those commands\n+\n+That keeps the feature honest. If the workflow feels clumsy after using the\n+primitives on real branches, then add a convenience `handoff` command above\n+them.\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n - [Future Use Cases](future-use-cases.md)\n - [Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md) - current turn/index-based association direction\n+- [Agent Session Handoff Design](handoff-design.md) - design notes for agent-to-agent catch-up\n - [Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) - older background on brittle association paths\n - [Capture Workflow](capture-workflow.md)\n - [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md)\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n - [Agentlog Sync Lifecycle](agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md)\n+- [Agent Session Handoff Design](handoff-design.md) - agent-to-agent catch-up design notes\n - [Agentlog Maintainability Playbook](maintainability-playbook.md)\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:30:41.608Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}